# AlfredOS custom AppArmor profile (#290) — userns exemption for the bwrap
# dual-LLM quarantine child.
#
# WHY THIS EXISTS
# ---------------
# The dual-LLM quarantine child (the ONLY component that touches raw T3 content)
# runs under `bubblewrap`, which builds an unprivileged user namespace to
# sandbox itself. On an Ubuntu 24.04+ / kernel-6.x host with
# `kernel.apparmor_restrict_unprivileged_userns=1` (the modern default), the
# kernel REFUSES unprivileged `unshare(CLONE_NEWUSER)` UNLESS the calling
# process runs under an AppArmor profile that carries the `userns,` permission.
# A container started with Docker's stock `docker-default` AppArmor profile does
# NOT carry it, so bwrap fails with:
#
#     bwrap: No permissions to create new namespace, likely because the kernel
#            does not allow non-privileged user namespaces.
#
# Applying THIS profile to the `alfred-core` (and any launcher-spawning) service
# via `security_opt: ["apparmor=alfred-bwrap"]` grants exactly that `userns,`
# permission so the sandbox can be built — WITHOUT `--privileged`, WITHOUT
# `CAP_SYS_ADMIN`, and WITHOUT flipping the host-wide
# `apparmor_restrict_unprivileged_userns` sysctl to 0 (which would lift the
# restriction for EVERY process on the host, not just our container).
#
# THE TRADE-OFF (documented for the security review)
# --------------------------------------------------
# `flags=(unconfined)` makes this profile a no-op AppArmor confinement — it
# REPLACES Docker's `docker-default` AppArmor confinement on the targeted
# container. We accept this narrowly because:
#
#   1. The userns exemption (`userns,`) is the whole point — and on current
#      AppArmor, a process can only be GRANTED userns by being under a profile
#      that allows it. A fully-enforcing custom profile that ALSO allow-lists
#      everything bwrap + CPython + the alfred runtime touch is far larger,
#      brittle across base-image/glibc bumps, and would itself need continuous
#      maintenance; `flags=(unconfined) { userns, }` is the pragmatic,
#      well-documented Ubuntu pattern for "let this one container do userns".
#   2. AppArmor is NOT the load-bearing containment for the quarantine child.
#      The real, kernel-enforced isolation around the T3 child is the bwrap
#      policy itself (`config/sandbox/quarantined-llm.linux.bwrap.policy`):
#      no /etc bind, synthesised /dev, unshared pid/uts/cgroup/ipc, tmpfs-only
#      writable surface, `--die-with-parent`. That policy is what the
#      adversarial sandbox-escape corpus asserts — it is unaffected by this
#      AppArmor profile.
#   3. The companion custom seccomp profile (`docker/seccomp/alfred-bwrap.json`)
#      stays in force (it is a separate `security_opt`): every Docker default
#      syscall deny is preserved EXCEPT the minimal namespace-syscall delta
#      bwrap needs. So syscall confinement is NOT dropped.
#
# Net: this profile trades AppArmor's (path-based) confinement on the core for
# the userns capability the dual-LLM sandbox requires, while seccomp confinement
# and the bwrap kernel-namespace containment remain fully in force.
#
# TIGHTER ALTERNATIVE (future work)
# ---------------------------------
# A non-`unconfined` profile that `include <abstractions/base>` + allow-lists
# the interpreter prefix, libs, and the bwrap mount operations and adds
# `userns,` would restore path-based confinement. It was deliberately deferred:
# it needs the in-image interpreter layout pinned first (the #290 interpreter
# sub-fix) and a dedicated hardening pass. Tracked as follow-up to #290.
#
# LOADING
# -------
# Host-side, one-time (needs root):
#     sudo apparmor_parser -r -W docker/apparmor/alfred-bwrap
# `bin/alfred-setup.sh` does this idempotently and skips gracefully where
# AppArmor is unavailable (macOS / non-AppArmor Linux).

abi <abi/4.0>,

include <tunables/global>

profile alfred-bwrap flags=(unconfined) {
  userns,
}
